<exercise number="5"><statement><p><ol label="a" cols="2">
    <li><p><m>h(t)=4^{-t} </m></p></li>
    <li><p><m>q(t)=-4^t </m></p></li>
</ol></p></statement>
<answer><p>
    <table><tabular left="minor" right="minor" top="minor" bottom="minor" halign="center"><col halign="left"/>
        <row>
            <cell><m>t</m></cell>
            <cell><m>-3</m></cell>
            <cell><m>-2</m></cell>
            <cell><m>-1</m></cell>
            <cell><m>0</m></cell>
            <cell><m>1</m></cell>
            <cell><m>2</m></cell>
            <cell><m>3</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
            <cell><m>h(t)=4^{-t} </m></cell>
            <cell><m>64</m></cell>
            <cell><m>16</m></cell>
            <cell><m>4</m></cell>
            <cell><m>1</m></cell>
            <cell><m>\frac{1}{4} </m></cell>
            <cell><m>\frac{1}{16} </m></cell>
            <cell><m>\frac{1}{64} </m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
            <cell><m>q(t)=-4^t </m></cell>
            <cell><m>\frac{-1}{64} </m></cell>
            <cell><m>\frac{-1}{16} </m></cell>
            <cell><m>\frac{-1}{4} </m></cell>
            <cell><m>-1</m></cell>
            <cell><m>-4</m></cell>
            <cell><m>-16</m></cell>
            <cell><m>-64</m></cell>
        </row>
    </tabular></table>
    <image source="images/fig-ans-4-2-5" alt="exponential decay and negative of growth" width="35%"/>
    The graphs are reflections of each other across the origin. Both are decreasing, but <m>h</m> has the negative <m>t</m>-axis as an asymptote, and <m>q</m> has the positive t-axis as its asymptote.
</p></answer>
</exercise>

